The '''Toyota bZ4X''', also marketed in Japan, US, Canada, Europe, and China as the '''Subaru Solterra''', is a [[Battery electric vehicle|battery electric]] [[compact crossover SUV]] manufactured by [[Toyota]]. The vehicle debuted in April 2021 as the "bZ4X Concept". It is the first vehicle to be based on the [[Toyota New Global Architecture#e-TNGA|e-TNGA platform]] co-developed by Toyota and [[Subaru]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=Toyota Reveals Electric SUV bZ4X Concept|url=https://insideevs.com/news/501743/toyota-bz4x-concept-electric-suv/|access-date=2021-04-19|website=InsideEVs|language=en|archive-date=8 November 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211108202848/https://insideevs.com/news/501743/toyota-bz4x-concept-electric-suv/|url-status=live}}</ref> and the brand's first model to be part of their [[Toyota bZ series|Toyota bZ]] ("beyond Zero") series of [[zero-emissions vehicle]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Toyota bZ4X concept is brand's first bespoke electric car|url=https://www.autocar.co.uk/car-news/new-cars/toyota-bz4x-concept-brands-first-bespoke-electric-car|access-date=2021-04-19|website=Autocar|language=en|archive-date=23 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210423090736/https://www.autocar.co.uk/car-news/new-cars/toyota-bz4x-concept-brands-first-bespoke-electric-car|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Toyota bZ4X Concept Debuts As Vision Of Future Electric Crossover|url=https://www.motor1.com/news/501565/toyota-bz4x-ev-concept-debut/|access-date=2021-04-19|website=Motor1.com|language=en|archive-date=19 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210419042235/https://www.motor1.com/news/501565/toyota-bz4x-ev-concept-debut/|url-status=live}}</ref>

Worldwide sales of the bZ4X commenced in mid-2022, with production planned in Japan and China.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Gauthier|first=Michael|date=2021-04-19|title=Toyota's bZ4X Concept Previews An Electric SUV Coming In 2022|url=https://www.carscoops.com/2021/04/toyotas-bz4x-concept-previews-an-electric-crossover-coming-in-2022/|url-status=live|access-date=2021-04-19|website=Carscoops|archive-date=19 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210419042234/https://www.carscoops.com/2021/04/toyotas-bz4x-concept-previews-an-electric-crossover-coming-in-2022/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Wren|first=Wesley|date=2021-04-19|title=The Toyota bZ4X Is Toyota's All-Electric Crossover of the Future|url=https://www.autoweek.com/news/future-cars/a36154293/toyota-bz4x-concept/|access-date=2021-04-19|website=Autoweek|language=en-US|archive-date=19 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210419042244/https://www.autoweek.com/news/future-cars/a36154293/toyota-bz4x-concept/|url-status=live}}</ref> Sales in the United States will also start in 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2021-04-19|title=Toyota's bZ4X Has a Funky Name, But Heralds a Serious New Electric Future|url=https://www.motortrend.com/news/toyota-bz4x-concept-first-look-review/|access-date=2021-04-19|website=MotorTrend|language=en|archive-date=19 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210419042233/https://www.motortrend.com/news/toyota-bz4x-concept-first-look-review/|url-status=live}}</ref> Toyota has also stated that there will be seven "bZ" models to be launched globally by 2025.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=Toyota Reveals Global Electrification Strategy in Shanghai |url=https://toyota.pressroom.com.au/press_release_detail.asp?clientID=2&prID=45748&navSectionID=2 |access-date=2021-04-19 |publisher=Toyota |location=Australia |archive-date=19 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210419042235/https://toyota.pressroom.com.au/press_release_detail.asp?clientID=2&prID=45748&navSectionID=2}}</ref>

== Name ==
According to Toyota, the meaning of the "bZ4X" nameplate breaks down into:
* "bZ": for "beyond Zero" emissions, representing the nature of a battery-electric vehicle by going "beyond Zero" emissions,
* "4": from the equivalent-sized [[Toyota RAV4]] and the
* "X": describing it as a compact crossover ('X') SUV.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://insideevs.com/news/500744/toyota-bz4x-electric-crossover-rav4/ |title=Toyota BZ4X Is The Name For Automaker's New Electric Crossover |first=Gustavo Henrique |last=Ruffo |work=InsideEVs |location=US |date=2021-04-13 |access-date=2021-12-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hotcars.com/heres-everything-we-love-about-the-new-toyota-bz4x-ev/ |title=Here's Everything We Love About The New Toyota bZ4X EV |first=Michael |last=De Kock |work=HotCars |location=Canada |date=2021-11-22 |access-date=2021-12-28}}</ref>

== Overview ==
The design of the bZ4X was previewed by pictures of a series of electric concept vehicles released by Toyota in June 2019. The company highlighted the plan to release six electric vehicles between 2020 and 2025, using the e-TNGA platform.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Alexander Stoklosa|date=2019-06-10|title=Toyota Details Six New EV Models Launching for 2020–2025|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a27887943/toyota-ev-rollout-plans/|access-date=2021-04-19|website=Car and Driver|language=en-US|archive-date=20 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210420134137/https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a27887943/toyota-ev-rollout-plans/|url-status=live}}</ref> The vehicle was also previewed by Subaru, which is developing the vehicle with Toyota as a concept mockup showcasing a similar concept design in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Beresford|first=Colin|date=2020-01-22|title=Subaru Gives First Look at Electric Crossover It Will Build with Toyota|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a30613610/subaru-crossover-concept-ev-hybrid-plans/|access-date=2021-04-19|website=Car and Driver|language=en-US|archive-date=19 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210419042233/https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a30613610/subaru-crossover-concept-ev-hybrid-plans/|url-status=live}}</ref>

The bZ4X Concept was revealed on 19 April 2021 and was presented at [[Auto Shanghai]] on the same day.<ref>{{Cite press release |url=https://global.toyota/en/newsroom/toyota/35083987.html |title=Toyota announces its new BEV series, Toyota bZ, in establishment of a full line-up of electrified vehicles |publisher=Toyota |date=2021-04-19 |access-date=2021-04-19 |archive-date=19 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210419022721/https://global.toyota/en/newsroom/toyota/35083987.html |url-status=live }}</ref> While it is revealed as a concept vehicle, the vehicle appeared to be nearly production-ready.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Goodwin|first=Antuan|title=Toyota BZ4X EV concept launches new 'Beyond Zero' branding|url=https://www.cnet.com/roadshow/news/toyota-bz4x-ev-concept-suv-debut/|access-date=2021-04-19|website=Roadshow|language=en|archive-date=19 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210419062522/https://www.cnet.com/roadshow/news/toyota-bz4x-ev-concept-suv-debut/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=2021-04-19|title=Toyota bZ4X Concept – RAV4-sized electric SUV developed with Subaru, yoke steering, coming 2022 – paultan.org|url=https://paultan.org/2021/04/19/toyota-bz4x-concept-rav4-sized-electric-suv-developed-with-subaru-yoke-steering-coming-2022/|access-date=2021-04-19|website=Paul Tan's Automotive News|language=en-US|archive-date=19 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210419055148/https://paultan.org/2021/04/19/toyota-bz4x-concept-rav4-sized-electric-suv-developed-with-subaru-yoke-steering-coming-2022/|url-status=live}}</ref> The bZ4X is similar in size to the RAV4, but stood lower with sharper styling and a longer wheelbase that matches the larger [[Toyota Highlander|Highlander]]'s.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Toyota bZ4X is the future of both Toyota and Subaru electric cars|url=https://www.autoblog.com/2021/04/18/toyota-bz4x-electric-crossover-etnga-platform-subaru-reveal/|access-date=2021-04-19|website=Autoblog|language=en|archive-date=19 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210419042234/https://www.autoblog.com/2021/04/18/toyota-bz4x-electric-crossover-etnga-platform-subaru-reveal/|url-status=live}}</ref> The vehicle has been developed in conjunction with Subaru, which is said to have had input into the car's [[all-wheel drive]] system.<ref>{{Cite web|title=New Toyota bZ4X previews electric SUV on sale in 2022|url=https://www.autoexpress.co.uk/toyota/353801/new-toyota-bz4x-previews-electric-suv-sale-2022|access-date=2021-04-19|website=Auto Express|language=en|archive-date=19 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210419042234/https://www.autoexpress.co.uk/toyota/353801/new-toyota-bz4x-previews-electric-suv-sale-2022|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Hoffman|first=Connor|date=2021-04-19|title=Toyota bZ4X Concept Previews First of Seven New bZ EVs|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a36144716/toyota-bz4x-concept-revealed/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210419042243/https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a36144716/toyota-bz4x-concept-revealed/|archive-date=19 April 2021|access-date=2021-04-19|website=Car and Driver|language=en-US}}</ref>

{{Clear left}}

== Design ==
The overall size, at {{cvt|4690|mm}} total length, is comparable to a [[RAV4]] ([[Toyota RAV4#XA50|XA50]]), but the wheelbase of {{cvt|2850|mm}} is similar to that of the [[Toyota Land Cruiser|Land Cruiser]] ([[Toyota Land Cruiser#J300|J300]]), giving the bZ4X a large interior space.<ref name="Watch-details" /> The e-TNGA platform was jointly developed by Toyota and Subaru, with Toyota receiving credit for battery and eAxle development and Subaru for all-wheel-drive control and collision safety.<ref name="Watch-details" />

Some models also adopt a [[steer-by-wire]] system.<ref name=Details_2021-10>{{Cite press release |url=https://global.toyota/en/newsroom/toyota/36254760.html |title=Details of All-New bZ4X BEV Announced |publisher=Toyota |access-date=2021-10-29 |date=2021-10-29 |archive-date=18 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211118003853/https://global.toyota/en/newsroom/toyota/36254760.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The steer-by-wire system was developed for the Chinese market and will be available with a [[Yoke (aeronautics)|yoke]] in lieu of a conventional steering wheel.<ref name=Watch-details>{{cite news |url=https://car.watch.impress.co.jp/docs/news/1362330.html |title=トヨタ、e-TNGA採用のバッテリEV新型車「bZ4X」詳細公表 スバルのAWD技術「X-MODE」採用するツインモーター4WDと、FWDモデルをラインアップ |language=ja |trans-title=Toyota announces details of new battery EV 'bZ4X' on e-TNGA platform; lineup includes FWD and twin-motor 4WD models with Subaru's 'X-MODE' AWD technology |author=谷川 潔 |date=October 29, 2021 |work=Car Watch |access-date=3 May 2022}}</ref> Combined with the low instrument panel, Toyota stated the yoke provides a more open interior.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://car.watch.impress.co.jp/docs/news/1320554.html |title=トヨタ、新型EV「TOYOTA bZ4X」に異形ハンドルのステアバイワイヤ世界初採用 |language=ja |trans-title=Toyota adopts steer-by-wire with yoke for the new EV 'TOYOTA bZ4X' for the first time worldwide |author=椿山和雄 |date=April 22, 2021 |work=Car Watch |access-date=3 May 2022}}</ref>

