=== Powertrains ===
[[File:Electric motor Toyota bZ4X Expo 2022 CRI 4894.jpg|thumb|Under-the-hood equipment, including the main [[power inverter]] (center), 12V accessory battery, and fusebox]]

The bZ4X is powered by the e-Axle, which integrates an electric motor, gears and [[Power inverter|inverter]], and is built by [[BluE Nexus]], a joint venture of [[Toyota Group]] companies [[Aisin]] and [[Denso]] with investment from Toyota Motor. Front-wheel drive models use a single ''1XM'' model e-Axle that produces {{convert|150|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}}, while all-wheel drive models use twin ''1YM'' model e-Axles that each produce {{convert|80|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}} for a combined output of {{convert|160|kW|hp PS|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{Cite web |date=5 June 2022 |title=TOYOTA bZ4X TECHNICAL SPECIFICATIONS |url=https://media.toyota.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/pdf/220605M-bZ4X-Tech-Spec.pdf |access-date=23 December 2022}}</ref>

Front-wheel drive models have an estimated range of {{convert|510|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} and a {{convert|0-100|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} time of 7.5 seconds, while all-wheel drive models have an estimated range of {{convert|460|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|0-100|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} time in 6.9 seconds.<ref name="Details_2021-10" /> On AWD models, the 'X-MODE' AWD-system from [[Subaru]] is "borrowed" from the [[Subaru Forester]].<ref name="Watch-details" />

Front-wheel drive models have a {{kWh|71.4|link=yes}} battery<ref name="Details_2021-10" /> built by Prime Planet Energy & Solutions (PPES), a joint venture between Toyota and Panasonic.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Kane |first=Mark |date=May 15, 2022 |title=Watch Toyota bZ4X AWD Fast Charging Test: 0-80% SOC Took One Hour |language=en |work=InsideEVs |url=https://insideevs.com/news/585939/toyota-bz4x-awd-fast-charging-curve/ |access-date=2022-08-04}}</ref> All-wheel drive models for the North American market have a {{kWh|72.8}} battery built by [[CATL]]. Both models are a 355&nbsp;volt pack that accepts DC fast charging at a maximum rate of 150&nbsp;kW for front-wheel drive models<ref name="Solterra-price" /> or 100&nbsp;kW for all-wheel drive models.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-05-01 |title=DC Fast Charging The Toyota bZ4X From 0-100% Is An Exercise In Patience! (AWD 72.8kWh CATL Battery) – YouTube |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8TzCMsKd8s8 |access-date=2022-05-01 |website= [[YouTube]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220501105329/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8TzCMsKd8s8 |archive-date=1 May 2022 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Using a fast charger can charge the PPES pack up to 80% capacity in 30 minutes, and an optional rooftop solar panel system may generate electricity to drive the vehicle for at least {{convert|1100|mi|km|abbr=on|order=flip}} per year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/cars/2021/10/29/toyota-bz-4-x-electric-vehicle-suv/6191912001/|title=Toyota bZ4X electric vehicle to arrive in 2022: Toyota's first EV makes debut|first=Nathan|last=Bomey|date=October 30, 2021|website=USA Today|access-date=8 December 2021|archive-date=2 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211202152534/https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/cars/2021/10/29/toyota-bz-4-x-electric-vehicle-suv/6191912001/|url-status=live}}</ref> The battery is estimated to retain 90% of its original capacity over a ten-year period.<ref name="Watch-details" /> The car can act as a power supply in [[vehicle-to-grid|V2H or V2L]] fashion.<ref name="Watch-details" />

