== Safety ==
On 23 June 2022, Toyota and Subaru [[Product recall|recalled]] 2,700 bZ4Xs and 2,600 Solterras due to the possibility that wheels could come loose. They also halted production and sales of any new models.<ref>{{Cite news |date=23 June 2022 |title=Toyota recalls 2,700 bZ4X EVs over potential risk wheels could come loose |work=Automotive News Europe |agency=Reuters |url=https://europe.autonews.com/automakers/toyota-recalls-2700-bz4x-evs-over-potential-risk-wheels-could-come-loose}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Recall issued for Toyota bZ4X and Subaru Solterra |url=https://www.electrive.com/2022/06/24/recall-issued-for-the-toyota-bz4x-and-the-subaru-solterra/ |access-date=2023-01-04 |website=electrive.com |language=en-US}}</ref>

On 6 October 2022, Toyota reported it has found a fix to the loose wheel recall and has resumed production of the bZ4X and Solterra.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Sugiyama |first=Satoshi |date=2022-10-06 |title=Toyota restarts output of first EV after fixing safety issues |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/autos-transportation/toyota-resume-selling-its-first-mass-produced-ev-after-safety-concern-recall-2022-10-06/ |access-date=2022-10-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-10-07 |title=Toyota BZ4X and Subaru Solterra twins back in production after wheels fell off |url=https://www.drive.com.au/news/toyota-bz4x-and-subaru-solterra-twins-back-in-production-after-wheels-fell-off/ |access-date=2023-01-04 |website=Drive |language=en-AU}}</ref>

The bZ4X and Solterra achieved a five star JNCAP rating from Japan's National Agency for Automotive Safety and Victim's Aid (NASVA) for comprehensive safety performance, based on testing conducted on a Subaru Solterra.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |title=SOLTERRA bZ4X/National agency for Automotive Safety & Victims' Aid |url=https://www.nasva.go.jp/mamoru/en/assessment_car/detail/241 |access-date=2022-11-08 |website=www.nasva.go.jp}}</ref>

